<text xml:lang="ta">
  <body>
    <div xml:id="PN379-intro">
      <p type="edition">tiṇai – atu. tuṟai – pariciṟṟuṟai. ōymāṉ villiyātaṉaip puṟattiṇai naṉṉākaṉār.
      </p>
      <p xml:lang="en" type="translation">  
      </p>
    </div>
    <div xml:id="PN379">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>yāṉē peṟukavaṉ ṟāṇiḻal vāḻkkai</l>
<l>yavaṉē peṟukaveṉ ṉāvicai nuvaṟa</l>
<l>ṉellari toḻuvar kūrvāṇ maḻuṅkiṟ</l>
<l>piṉṉai maṟattō ṭariyak kalcet</l>
<l>taḷḷal yāmaik kūṉpuṟat turiñcu</l>
<l>nellamal puravi ṉilaṅkai kiḻavōṉ</l>
<l>villi yātaṉ kiṇaiyēm peruma</l>
<l>kuṟuntā ḷēṟṟaik koḻuṅka ṇavviḷar</l>
<l>naṟuney yurukki nāṭcō <supplied>ṟīyā</supplied></l>
<l>valla ṉentai pacitīrt talleṉak</l>
<l>koṉvaral vāḻkkainiṉ kiṇaivaṉ kūṟak</l>
<l>kēṭṭataṟ koṇṭum vēṭkai taṇṭātu</l>
<l>viṭṭōy talaiya kuṉṟam piṉpaṭa</l>
<l>.......................ra vantaṉeṉ yāṉē tāyi</l>
<l>ṟūvāk kuḻavi pōla vāṅkat</l>
<l>tiruvuṭait tirumaṉai yaitutōṉṟu kamaḻpukai</l>
<l>varumaḻai maṅkuliṉ maṟukuṭaṉ maṟaikkuṅ</l>
<l>kuṟumpa<supplied>ṭu kuṇṭakaḻ</supplied> nīṇmati lūrē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>  “I, let me get a living in the shade of his foot. (1)</l>
<l>He, let him get fame by the utterances of my tongue. (2) </l>
<l>O great man, we are the Kiṇai players of Villiyātaṉ, (7)</l>
<l>lord of Laṅkā, [its] fields dense with paddy, (6)</l>
<l>where, when [their] sharp sickles become blunt, the paddy-cutting workmen (3) </l>
<l>think of stones that are difficult [to find] for [their] earlier force (4) </l>
<l>and rub [them] against rubs the humped backs of the tortoises in the mire, (5)</l>
<l>melting in white fragrant ghee with fat-eyes</l>
<l>the short-legged male [and] giving the rice of the day (8f.) </l>
<l>our father is able to remove hunger”, (10)</l>
<l>upon taking in what we heard (12ab)</l>
<l>when so told your Kiṇai player, with a living by coming early, (11)</l>
<l>	desire not cooling down, (12cd)</l>
<l>while hills with sky-touching peaks were left behind (13)</l>
<l>………………… I came (14)</l>
<l>to that place like a calf that has not eaten without a mother, (15)</l>
<l>to [your] village with tall fortifications [and] a murderous deep moat, a stronghold, (18)</l>
<l>where fragrant smoke appearing wonderfully from those auspicious houses that possess Śrī, (16)</l>
<l>hides all the streets like coming rain clouds. (17)</l>
</lg>
    </div>
